    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Asking for Directions",
      "explanation": "To ask where something is, use 'Gdje je...?' (Where is...?) followed by the place. For asking how to get somewhere, use 'Kako mogu doći do...?' (How can I get to...?). The preposition 'do' (to/until) takes the genitive case. When giving directions, Croatians use imperative forms: 'Idite' (Go - formal), 'Skrenite' (Turn - formal). You can add 'molim Vas' (please, formal) to be extra polite.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Where is the pharmacy?",
          "target_primary": "Gdje je ljekarna?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "How can I get to the beach?",
          "target_primary": "Kako mogu doći do plaže?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Go straight, then turn right.",
          "target_primary": "Idite ravno, pa skrenite desno.",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Is it far?",
          "target_primary": "Je li daleko?",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Getting Around Croatia",
      "content": "Croatia's coastline is its crown jewel, and ferries (trajekti) operated by Jadrolinija are essential for island-hopping along the Adriatic. The word 'kolodvor' is distinctly Croatian (Serbian uses 'stanica' for train station). Zagreb has an efficient tram (tramvaj) network that has been running since 1891. In Dalmatian coastal cities like Dubrovnik and Split, many old town areas are pedestrian-only, so walking is the primary way to explore. Taxis and ride-sharing apps are available in major cities. When asking locals for directions, many Croatians - especially younger generations - speak good English, but attempting Croatian is always appreciated."
    }
